::concept id="zod.object-schema" title="Zod object schema" kind="library-concept" tags="typescript validation tools agents"

::summary
A Zod object schema describes the shape of a JavaScript object while the program is running.

TypeScript types are erased after compilation. Zod schemas still exist at runtime, so generated JSON can be checked before real code executes.
::end

::why
An LLM can request a tool call with JSON arguments.

Those arguments are untrusted until the runtime validates them.

`z.object({ a: z.number(), b: z.number() })` means the value must be an object with numeric `a` and `b` fields.
::end

::example
```ts
const schema = z.object({
  a: z.number(),
  b: z.number(),
});

const args = schema.parse({ a: 2, b: 5 });
```
::end

::docs
title="Zod documentation"
url="https://zod.dev/"
why="Use this for the official schema, parsing, and validation APIs."
::end

::end

::concept id="agent.tool-contract" title="Agent tool contract" kind="runtime-concept" tags="agents tools runtime"

::summary
A tool contract is the boundary between a model request and code that can actually run.
::end

::why
The contract names the tool, explains what it does, defines the input schema, and provides the execute function.

That lets the runtime decide whether a model request is valid before calling application code.
::end

::example
```ts
defineTool({
  name: "add",
  description: "Add two numbers",
  schema,
  execute: ({ a, b }) => ({ result: a + b }),
});
```
::end

::end

::concept id="runtime.validation" title="Runtime validation" kind="runtime-concept" tags="validation agents safety"

::summary
Runtime validation checks values when the program is executing, not only when TypeScript compiles.
::end

::why
Tool calls cross a trust boundary. The model may emit invalid JSON, missing fields, or the wrong value types.

Validation catches that before the runtime runs the tool.
::end

::example
```ts
const parsed = schema.parse(modelArgs);
return tool.execute(parsed);
```
::end

::end

::reference id="tool-contract-card" title="Tool contract" kind="recall-card" reveal="shape-without-answer"

::body
A useful tool definition has four pieces:

- `name`
- `description`
- `schema`
- `execute`

For the add tool, the schema should require numeric `a` and `b`.
::end

::links
