::step id="tool-contracts" title="Introduce tool contracts"

::explain concepts="zod.object-schema agent.tool-contract runtime.validation"
Agent tools need more than TypeScript types.

The model sends JSON, and JSON arrives at runtime. That is why a tool contract combines [[agent.tool-contract|a named tool contract]] with [[zod.object-schema|a Zod object schema]] and [[runtime.validation|runtime validation]].
::end

::edit id="export-tool-helper" path="src/index.ts" mode="append" typing="ghost" anchor="index.public-api"

::note when="start"
Expose the helper from the package entrypoint so consumers can import it.
::end

```ts

export { defineTool } from "./tools/tool.js";
```
::end

::explain focus="index.public-api" concepts="agent.tool-contract"
The public boundary now exports the type surface and the helper function.

That means consumer code can import `defineTool` from the package entrypoint instead of reaching into internal folders.
::end

::end

::step id="define-add-tool-step" title="Define the first real tool"

::recall id="define-add-tool" path="src/demo/tools.ts" references="tool-contract-card" uses="zod.object-schema agent.tool-contract runtime.validation" difficulty="supported-recall"

::task
Create an `addTool` using `defineTool`.

It should accept `{ a: number, b: number }` and return `{ result: a + b }`.
::end

::support

::intent
Create the first real tool contract.
::end

::concepts
[[zod.object-schema|Zod object schema]]
[[agent.tool-contract|Tool contract]]
[[runtime.validation|Runtime validation]]
::end

::api
`defineTool({ name, description, schema, execute })`

`z.object({ a: z.number(), b: z.number() })`
::end

::mental-model
The model may request a tool call, but the runtime should not trust model-generated JSON.

The schema is the gate between model output and real code execution.
::end

::common-mistake
Do not use `z.object({})` for a tool that needs `a` and `b`.

An empty object schema does not describe the numeric arguments your tool needs.
::end

::end

::verify id="verify-add-tool" kind="agent"

::goal
Verify that consumers can import the tool helper and define a typed add tool with a runtime Zod schema.
::end

::evidence
files="src/index.ts src/tools/tool.ts src/demo/tools.ts"
terminal_command="npm run typecheck"
terminal_output="latest"
::end

::rubric
Pass if `src/index.ts` exports `defineTool` and the useful tool type surface.
Pass if `src/demo/tools.ts` defines `addTool` with `defineTool`.
Pass if the add tool schema requires numeric `a` and `b` using Zod.
Pass if execute returns `{ result: a + b }`.
Do not require exact ordering.
Do not pass if TypeScript fails.
::end

::messages
success="Nice. Tool definitions are now part of the public runtime API."
failure="The add tool is not a valid typed tool contract yet."
::end

::end

::end

